Skeleton of an apparently healthy 19 year old boy, c. 174 cm tall. The body was in a contracted position, with its head to the north, lying on its right side facing west. The hands were placed on the knees, but the pit was clearly too small for the occupant , whose head was jammed vertically against the side of the pit (Cruse and Harrison 1983, 84).

Former RM North Barracks (Anderson in Parfitt 2000, 10): A total of 172 grams of cremated human bone was recovered. All the bones are off white, completely burnt and highly fragmented.No bone elements were duplicated; as such, only one individual is represented. The largest fragment, weighing 12 gms, was a portion of a humeral head. The fact that the proximal humeral epiphysis was fully fused indicates that the remains are adult. The small size of the incomplete mandible condyle might suggest that the remains are female.

South Willesborough (Deeves 2002): a small amount of cremated bone, including tooth crowns, along with charcoal fragments. The bone was identified to be that of an infant, with the age of death being around 6 months.

Dumpton Down Barrow, Intercutting Grave Pits A-C, Burial 1  (Perkins 2004, 77): Hr: Crouched inhumation burial - no further details available, no gg. C14 dated 2140 to 1880 cal BC (95%) (BM-2957) (3630 +/- 45 BP).

South Dumpton Down (Perkins 1994, 12-6, fig. 9): Crouched burial, carefully placed within a pit. 'The skeletal remains were in very good condition and were those of a well built adult ... The position of the skeleton: lying on its right side with legs flexed and right forearm and hand above the skull (shielding the face with a fold of cloak?), is very different from the 'chucked in the hole' appearance of other burials on site. After the the burial bad been placed, dumping' (Perkins 2004, 12 fig. 9)
Too little calcined bone (1-4mm) was recovered to positively identify it as human (Sibun in Stevens 2003, 92).Total weight: 15gFragment size: highly fragmented (2-14mm)Skeletal elements present: n/a
Westhawk Farm (Booth et al 2008): 703g cremated human remains, probably from an adult man. No further details are available.
Springhead Northfleet: No further details available
Poorly preserved skeleton of an 18-25 year old woman (25-30% survived). Evidence of stress/disease in childhood (dental hyperplasia) and of poor dental hygiene (White 2006, 3)

Monkton (Area 4) Grave 751 Skeleton 2a (Bennett et al 2008, 15):A cluster of disarticulated human bone was located behind the legs of the crouched inhumation. This included the partial remains of a child, aged 8-10. Collagen from the bones was c14 dated to 2289 to 1925 cal BC (BM-2923, 95% confidence).Overall the disarticulated bones may represent rearranged bones from an earlier disturbed burial or bodies that were excarnated prior to burial at the same time as the main burial in this grave.

Monkton (Area 4) Grave 751 Skeleton 1 (Bennett et al 2008, 15):The primary burial was a single crouched inhumation of a young adult man (19-22), head to the S, facing E. Collagen from his bone was c14 dated to 2180-1890 cal BC (BM-2898, 95% confidence)

Margetts Pit (Wessex Archaeology 2010) pit 856: LBA pit containing 0.5g burnt human bone from a teenager (table 6, 36)NB this feature is identified as a 'ritual/?mortuary deposit' rather than a cremation burial in the report (2010, 36, 38)
<Former Hawkinge Aerodrome (Preistly-Bell 2002) F. 148>:Contained cremated human bone (no further details)

Mostly well-fired cremated human remains recovered from two separate fills of a burial pit (Sibun in Margetts 2012, 51-3). The material from the separate fills is summarised separately here, although it was not possible to tell during the assessment of this material whether more than one person was represented (there were no duplicate bones). Traces of cu-alloy staining were observed on fragments of metatarsel:Primary pit fill:Total weight: 352gFragment size: 0->30mmSkeletal elements present: Skull, arms, legsSecondary pit fill:Total weight: 396g (including the weight of small stones in this sample ...)Fragment size: 0-30mmSkeletal elements present: Skull, arms, legs

The bone itself in a good state of preservation but highly fragmented - c. 60-75% of the skeleton survived. Additional small fragments of human bone were recovered from an environmental sample taken from the grave fill (Sibun in Margetts 2012, 51).

140g in total of variably fired human bone distributed throughout the fill of the cremation pit but concentrated in the middle/originally at the bottom of the pot (Vessel 4) (see Moody et al 2010, 162-3 for further details).Total weight: 140gFragment size: n/aSkeletal elements present: tooth

Tothill Street, Minster: One of three LIA inhumations from the cemetery that were deposited with objects.This record represents a supine inhumation burial with a pot of unknown form/condition. No further information is available.

Partially articulated adult male burial (c. 40% body represented) (aged c. 30-35) arranged in a neat bundle (probably bagged or bound) and laid semi-prone on his left side. His arms appear to have been bent backwards, behind the back. The skull was perched on top of the bundle, slumped backwards in an awkward position such that the top of the head rested on the arm. The body was probably substantially decomposed upon deposition. Isotope analysis suggested that this person may have been of Scandinavian origin  (McKinley 2014, Burial 3673, 41, 96-7, fig. 2.17).
This cremation was in a Beaker (unusual) and in a pit grave that also contained an inhumation
Poorly preserved remains of an inhumation (probably originally crouched). In the same grave and possibly accompanied by a Beaker hat had the cremation (HR 50099) in it

Efficiently cremated bone from an adult (Sibun in Dawkins 20120, 34).Total weight: 1100g (967g from within the urn; 133g probably representing disturbed material distributed in the wider pit fill)Fragment size: mostly 5-20 mmSkeletal elements present: Skull, axial, upper limb, lower limb
Crouched inhumation burial <awaiting further details>

848g cremated human remains, probably from a man, burnt with his flesh on. Slight evidence of joint degeneration. Only c. 68% of the bone within the deposit was fully burnt, while some fragments were unburnt or only slightly charred (Gibson et al. in Allen et al. 2012, 301-2).Total weight: 848gFragment size: mostly >5mmSkeletal elements present: Dominated by cranial fragments but occasional axial, upper and lower limb fragments were also identified

Possible very degraded inhumation in pit cut into old ground surface with bracer, arrowhead and Beaker sitting on top of it. On old ground surface

Very poorly preserved remains of an 18-25 year old of unclear sex. The right arm was flexed and lay beneath or near the head and the left was placed across the chest. Due to the degraded condition of the bone very little pathological information was observed and the isotope analysis was not informative (McKinley in Stevenson 2013, 154).

Brisley Farm, Kent (Stevenson 2013): Poorly preserved remains of a young man (c. 18-25). The body was supine with the head at the south end. There was a slight twist to the remains with the hips pushed towards the east wall of the grave. Therefore the feet were centrally placed but the head was in the south-west corner of the grave. The arms lay at the sides of the body (Stevenson 2013, 160). Due to the degraded condition of the bone very little pathological information was observed (McKinley in Stevenson 2013, 161)

OLd male >50 yrs with broken but fully healed fibula. He was flexed on left side woth a Food Vessel behind his head. Note Food Vessels are very rare in Kent and this is only one of three sites where Food Vessels have been encountered as grave goods
Inhumation burial. 7 bone fragments; skull. Adult >18 years, unsexed? (Riddler, McKinley and Skittrell 2006, 6).
St Stephen's College, N Foreland Flat Grave (Perkins 1999): Crouched burial of an adult. cranial - pelvic axis 350¡ NNW, skeletal material in very good condition.
Ellington School MBA urned cremation burial F25 (Boden 2006, McNee 2012): Cremated remains deposited within a ceramic vessel. No further details available.

Cremated bone which appeared to 'issue from the mouth' of the collared urn vessel (Boast et al. 2011, 42). No further details available. Very small quantity of cremated bone (17.2g) - and neither age nor sex could be identified.

Cremated human remains with identifiable fragments of skull, upper limbs and lower limbs, although further analysis on the bone was not possible (Askew 2006, 16).
<75 The Street, Hawkinge (Thorne 2006, 19) Cremation Set II>:Hr: c. 800g cremated human bone from an adult (Sibun in Thorne 2006, table 4)

<Museum of Thanet's Virtual Museum, North Foreland III, 1999, Burial 1 (internal barrow burial)>The bones which remained in the central rectangular grave indicated that they belonged to an adult of approximately 25-35 years of age. The body had been laid in a crouched position with the head to the south, facing west.The grave was only around 0.30m deep, but the surviving soil backfill suggested that the body may had been laid within a wooden coffin-structure (Boast, Gardner and Moody 2006).

<Museum of Thanet's Virtual Museum, North Foreland III, 1999, Burial 2 (ditch burial)>Within the grave were the remains of a child, perhaps between 9-10 years of age (of unknown sex). The body had been laid in a crouched position on its right-hand side, with the head facing south-east. The tightly crouched position suggests that child's body may have been bound or wrapped before it was placed within the grave (Boast, Gardner and Moody 2006).

Crouched inhumation of older male with a series of grave goods and likely contained within a coffin. Adjacent to the head was a comb decorated Beaker vessel. The Beaker is an early type, equating to Clarke's Wessex/Mid Rhine Group or step 3 of the Lanting and van der Waals scheme, thought to date to around 2300 BC. The skeleton though was radiocarbon dated to 1902 (+/- 33) BC. This apparently conforms to a recognised local pattern of late dates for apparently early Beaker styles. Other grave goods found with the burial were three barbed and tanged flint arrowheads found near the lower back, an angular flint in the chest area and a tiny fragment of amber near the head.Decayed oak coffin structure. Chalk packed around coffin structure Crouched with pot behind head and head at N
East Kent Access Route (Zone 13, Burial 200062): Skeleton of an older adult man (c. 35-45 years old) (90% skeletal parts present) placed in a flexed position on his left hand side.

East Kent Access Route (Zone 21 ring ditch): Sub-adult 16-19 years old. She lay on her side with flexed limbs. Arms in front of body crossed; quite an unusual position. Pieces of a tibia and fibula suggest an adult skeleton. Sex not determined.Total weight: c. 100gFragment size: not knownSkeletal elements present: tibia, fibia

Partly cremated partly still inhumed burial; with cremated bone in a fully articulated position crouched on right side. had been laid on a funeral pile. Very large male with delicate teeth; pot in front of face. This is an interesting burial as it seems almost transition. It is following inhumnation customs but with a cremation twist. Also note that the Collared Urn is placed by the head of the person and does not contain the cremated remains which of course are not raked up anyway.

In pit 450m east of Grave 1. Degraded but accompanied by flat axe & 2 flat riveted daggers. Note the bones may not have been as degraded as originally thought and are in Maidstone museum. Also note the bones were stained green suggesting the daggers were likely close to the arms of the individual and the the axe (hafted when deposited) was by the legs James (quoted in Ashbee 1997: 152) <however, said that < 'The bones had been taken out, or rather had fallen out of the side of the cliff before my arrival, so that I had to depend entirely upon the word of the workmen as to the depth beneath the surface'.>These bones, displayed with the bronzes in Maidstone Museumduring the 1930s, showed that they may have been far from fragile. It may well be that the daggers were close by the arms of the corpse and that the axe, hafted when deposited, was by the legs. R.F. Jessup (1930, 116) noted this interment, the axe and daggers, and said that these, together with ' ...part of a skeleton, are now in Maidstone Museum', and added that 'It seems from the meagre account that there was no mound over the grave>
'Halling Man': Unusual burial as body was covered by a layer of flints 12 to 18 inches thick. There were also a large number of shells found representing 31 species.

<Duffy and MacGregor 2007, Swainbost, N. Uist>: partial remains of a coastally-eroded in-situ human burial remains were found to be from one individual, probably male, aged between 30-34 years at death with a slight deformity of the spine buried in a supine position in a flat-based grave. A single radiocarbon date suggests burial dates to 390-170 BC. Only a limited portion of the burial was still preserved in-situ including both legs and feet, and the left lower arm and hand; enough, however, remained to identify the burial as a supine inhumation (north-east  to  south-west). Other skeletal elements including the torso of the skeleton were found to have slumped down the slope by c l m.<Duffy in Duffy and MacGregor 2007, 158>: An unusual pathology  was noted on lumbar vertebrae 1 and 2, where the left inferior articular facet of both elements was rotated medially, and shortened by up to 4.8 mm compared to the right inferior articular facet. This pattern also apparent on the first sacral vertebrae, where the left superior articular facet appeared to be slightly rotated medially. No other osseous response was not although much of the rest of the vertebral column was fragmented. The causes of this pathology are not immediately clear. No evidence of a fracture to either spinous process was observed, although it is possible that it is an osseous response to a poorly healed vertebral fracture further up the spinal column. It is also possible that the abnormality may have a genetic origin.rc dates on human bone: SUERC-5368; Human Left Ulna; 2210 +/- 40; 386-183 cal BC Oxcal v.4 (95% confidence)

<Barber et al. 1989, Hornish Point>: The dismembered body of a 12 year old boy was distributed between the pits.The human remains in Pit 1 were contained within a setting of four vertically positioned stones. Chop marks were found on the spinal column suggesting dismemberment at the time of death or soon after. Diagonal chops were applied to his back, slicing through the trunk between the waist and the hip. The mixing of body parts in two of the pits also suggested partial decomposition prior to burial (hence a few bones were not in articulated groups). The boy suffered from a slight strain of spina bifida which may or may not have had any physical effects. The human and animal bodies were distributed as follows:Pit 1: hr included lower body parts including the lower right limb and part of the pelvic girdle; animal remains included substantial parts of a juvenille cow/bull (18-30 months in age)Pit 2: hr included the upper trunk, upper limbs and skull of the boyPit 3: hr included the lower trunk, part of the pelvic girdle and stray bones (eg finger, clavicle); animal remains included substantial parts of two female sheep (one 18-30 months in age, the other 3+ years)Pit 4: hr included the boy's left foot. animal remains included substantial parts of a juvenille cow/bull (slightly older than the example in Pit 1)

<Barrowman and Innes 2009, Pabay Mor>: mature male of approximately 50Ð59 years of age, placed in a grave adjacent to a marker stone. The burial was crouched and aligned northÐsouth. A radiocarbon date of 1450Ð1290 cal BC (GU-13838) was obtained from human bone from the burial.<Duffy in Barrowman and Innes 2009>: Overall  the  adult  showed  well-developed  muscle markings throughout his skeleton, with the right side showing particular muscle development, poten- tially indicating right-handedness. An enthesopathy was also noted at the insertion of tibialis anterious on the left tibia, although the complex aetiology of such osseous changes precludes any assignment of causal factors. Overall these observations indicate that he pursued a vigorous lifestyle and was probably well muscled.Evidence of spinal joint disease was also noted, almost exclusively conÞned to the cervical portion of the spinal column ... The  relatively advanced stage of this condition further reinforces the picture of a vigorous lifestyle and repeated spinal column stress, potentially through heavy lifting and carrying of heavy objects on the back.Dental health was found to be good, although the mandibular teeth were highly worn. Calculus was slight where it existed, and there was a complete absence of evidence of periodontal disease, caries or abscess formation ...Despite his age, no evidence of osteoarthritis was observed on any of the articular surfaces of the adult. This may further strengthen the suggestion that the observed spinal joint disease has a more speciÞc cause than advanced age or a general vigorous lifestyle alone, as osteoarthritic changes may also have reasonably been expected if general age and lifestyle were the causes.

Cremated bones (no further info).Aldridge (2005, 178) notes (based on Anderson and Andrews' unpublished human bone report) that overall, the cremated bone from the site indicates that cremation took place in a well-oxygenated environment with temperatures in excess of 500¡c. Based on the weight of bone, it appears that on average only c. 11 per cent of each adult body was recovered, with a range of c.5-c.22 per cent. The majority of bone fragments were under 25mm, with the mean weight of identified fragments being 0.71gms.

Cremated remains and other deposits in pit 6132 (Hayden 2006, 159): 11g cremated human bone representing a teenager, heaped together as a small deposit at the base of the pit - no bone was showing on the surface of the feature (Witkin 2006, 8).NB the description of this deposit in the human remains report contradicts that in the main site report (Hayden 2006) where it is suggested that 292g burnt bone was recovered from this pit. The info about the grave goods/burial context in the human remains report (Witkin 2006) is also inaccurate ... The CTRL scheme-wide human bone report (Mckinley 2006) does not included feature nos. making it impossible to link the information from this with specific burials.

The articulated skeleton of an older adult male (aged 40-52) lay supine with his head to the SE within this pit. The right arm was extended; the left arm bent so that the hand lay on the upper left hand side of the chest. The position of the pelvis, at the SW edge of the pit, and of the remains of the left foot, adjacent to the pelvis, suggests that the legs were drawn up over the lower torso, perhaps simply to fit the corpse into a small pit. The legs and skull in particular were damaged, probably because they were nearest the top of the pit (Hayden 2006, 158; see also Witkin 2006).Degenerative joint disease was recorded on the cervicals, the thoracic and lumbar vertebrae, the right shoulder, both wrists, and the fingers. The, right 4th metacarpal was fractured. Considerable periodontal disease and dental caries were evident.

Carefully arranged fragments from cranium, mandible, fibula shaft and rib. The long bones had been positioned so as to form three sides of a trapezium within which the skull had been placed. The mandible lay outside this trapezium with the teeth facing down.Cut marks on the skull - 2 healed chop marks on the parietals, 4 smaller nicks on the left parietal. Dental caries and abcess. Healed porotic hyperostosis on the skull, potentially as a result of anaemia (Witkin 2006, 9; see also Walker et al. 2009)

Burial W1411 (Riddler and Trevarthen 2006, 16): Probable inhumation burial disturbed by later grave cut. No unburnt bone was identified in the grave but this could be explained by the poor bone preservation generally on the site and the later disturbance of this grave.It is also worth noting that the information about human remains from this grave is contradictory. The grave plan shows skeletal fragments (1449) however the human remains report mentions only the redeposited cremated remains. An early account of the site mentions six inhumation burials. None of the numbers allocated to human remains link up between reports so this issue is impossible to resolve.

On the floor of this, at the latter end, was an adult skeleton (No. 1), head to the west, on the right side, the left arm bent to a right angle over the chest, with the hand near the right elbow, while the right arm was stretched by the side of the skeleton with the hand turned along the left femur. The knees were brought up to form nearly a right angle with the body. The extreme lengths of a femur and a tibia were 17  inches and 14  inches respectively. The right humerus measured 12  inches, while the left humerus measured 12.5 inches only, and was of less substance. At the feet was a crushed food-vase in a very disturbed condition The skeleton was lying on a decomposed wooden coffin

One skull inverted and the other reversed; with part of FV.These were either disturbed earlier burials or had been excarnated elsewhere and redeposited here. Although Mortimer (1905: 330) also suggests that:<The confusion of the bones might be due to the bodies at the bottom having been placed sitting on their hips-as in a few other instances-with a covering of wood above them, on which had been placed another body in a recumbent posture. In time these would fall in by decay.>

Under the central burial with FV of soil upon the floor of the grave. The west end of the grave deepened a little, where, partly under the interment just described, were the dismembered bones of two youths (Nos. 2 and 3) of about the ages of 13 and 15 years respectively. They were in the greatest disorder. One skull had its base upwards, the other being in a reversed position, the lower jaw being a foot distant from either skull ; and none of the leg bones were articulated. These remains were accompanied by portions of a food-vase placed in two heaps a foot apart. These were either disturbed earlier burials or had been excarnated elsewhere and redeposited here

Elderly woman placed in a flexed position on her left side, with her right arm extended above her head, elbow bent and index finger pointed (c. 99% body represented). The left hand held a piece of chalk and was bent to the mouth, as if to take a bite out of it. Two further burials (a juvenile withough grave goods, and subadult GID_hr71344) slightly overlapped with this burial) (McKinley 2014, Burial 3675, 43, 96-7).This woman was killed by a series of blows to the head with a sharp long-bladed weapon - probably a sword (see GID50171_2_GIDhr71342trauma_McKinley2014_pl4.6).

Juvenile (aged 10-12 years) placed in a crouched position on the right side (c. 98% body represented). The body was slightly twisted with the legs slumped far to the right and the thorax in an almost supine position. The hands were together (potentially tied) under the chin. The skull, although still articulated, had been twisted round so that it sat on its base, facing the associated half pot. This may represent post-decompositional manipulation (McKinley 2014, Burial 3676, 43, 96-7).

Young woman (c. 17-18 years old) placed in a flexed position on her right hand side (c. 99% body represented). Her head was slumped forwards towards her chest and right shoulder. Her right arm was placed, slightly bent, across the body; her left hand was touching her left shoulder. Her legs were tightly flexed. The body appeared to have slumped from a more upright position following deposition (McKinley 2014, Burial 3680, 43-4, 96-7).There was a healed fracture to the little toe (McKinley 2014, 123)

Probably male subadult buried on his left side with legs flexed and arms extended. His hands were placed over his pelvis and his head was bent down. The centre of the barrow was tunnelled into a small rectangular stone cist was found. A quantity of burnt (sic cremated) bones lay on the floor of the cist. Thus it was an unurned cremation burial.Reanalysis of the cremated bones suggests that it was probably an adult female, 18-39 years old. A radiocarbon date on the cremated bone gave a determination of 2130-1890 cal BC (GrA-32127; 3625±35); i.e, Early Bronze Age. The date is intriguing as these grave goods have been generally considered to be more in keeping with Wessex II (ie later than this date and moving towards 1750Ð1500 BC).

Found in an unusual two-storey cist. Upper storey was empty and in lower storey was the flexed inhumation of a youth c 13-15 years old overlying and a cremation with a deerhorn. The wisdom teeth of this individual had not erupted. skeleton of a young person in a flexed position, with the feet drawn up behind. It was lying on its right side with the head to the north. The skull, which was almost entire, was very frail and so much decomposed that there were several holes in it; indicated an individual of about fifteen years of age; the frontal suture was ossified, but the wisdom teeth had not emerged from their sockets. The femur measured only 11 inches and the tibia 9 inches.
Cremation in double cist - lying in east end of lower chamber with inhumation partly overlying it The cremation was fully encased in a woven basket

Cist 1 had crouched adult male >25, in fact possibly quite old, 5 ft 3" with broken ribs ; cremated bones on feet and legs. Note some foot bones moved to SE corner of cistgrave goods (two very rude stone tools) were placed on top of the capstone cover This is not a complete inhumation
Pile of cremated bones of possible female on feet and legs. The cremation also had quite a lot of cramp/ pyre slag adhering to the bones

Eastling Wood, Phase 3 Grave 687 (Bennett et al 2014, 29-30):hr: The burial was that of a child, aged approximately eight years. Unusually, the child was laid on its back, with head to the north-east and tilted to face west. The legs were tightly flexed. The left upper arm was at an angle to the body, the forearm bent back across the rib cage with the hand resting high on the chest. The right upper arm lay parallel to the body with forearm at right angles, resting vertically against the side of the grave. Skeleton 692 provided a date of 1737-1531 cal BC (lab no UBA20689)

Eastling Wood, Phase 3 Grave 439 (Bennett et al 2014, 30-2, fig. 21):Sk 623:hr: The primary burial (SK 623) was of a child aged approximately five years laid on its right side, head to the north-west, facing south-west, with legs tightly flexed. The left arm was laid parallel with the body, with the forearm flexed and across the waist. The right upper arm lay parallel with the front of the body. Bone from the child provided a radiocarbon date of 1520-1280 cal BC (lab no 130971)

Pot contained charcoal, 'foreign' earth and a pair of burnt infant ear bones (petrous bones). Carefully selected. Placed in pot J. A small Primary series Collared Urn. NO other bone in this pot Are these ear bones a grave good rather than a token burial?
Pot H. 2700g of adult cremation. Full cremation. Carefully cleaned and collected. He suffered from osteoarthritis and was likely an older adult . Pot filled to top

Pot B contained 550g of burnt bone - mainly skull & long bones; also vertebrae. Cleaned and sorted. A further 225 g of burnt bone were scattered outside the pot - same person. And adult male. It looks like the bone was taken from the pyre in two operations so perhaps not very careful on first sweep. The pot had been plugged with blob of red clay (possibly from the pyre) and sealed before second sweep.

In inverted Collared Urn probably in a pit. No detail about the nature of the human remains. In Collared Urn with flared neck & rim. About 1864, two urns with burnt bones were found near the landing stage for steamers at Menai Bridge. The finders destroyed one; the other has also since perished. Within one of the urns lay a bronze pin about 3.5 inches long; one end pointed, the other flat, in like fashion as bronze 'awls' often found in urns in Wiltshire. One of the urns was sketched, showing no ornament although of unusual fashion. A bronze blade was lately found amongst burned bones at the same spot 2.5 inches long, 5/8 inch breadth. <1>2 urns, 1 containing bronze awl and 'bronze blade' amongst burnt bones. Middle Bronze Age. (RCAHMW, 1937)

Inhumation with Beaker. Flexed (actually crouched) inhumation in cist with AOC early Beaker - unusual for Wales!  Decayed body of adult male >25 years old & on right side with head to N & intact Beaker upright at feet. He was very tall - nearly 6 foot (1.86m). The inhumation is unfortunately rather degraded

In cist was a layer of cremated bones and pyre material in a leather bag  - the grave goods were placed at one end of the cist and the pots were placed on their sides with the mouths facing each other and on top of cremated remains
Unurned and within the cist were the cremated boned of a man. Near the cist on the original floor were patches of charcoal, a few fragments of cremated bone and small flints with secondary working.

Likely a degraded inhumation that was crouched. Before the cist was closed, a small globular bowl Food Vessel sf2038 was placed inside the compartment. It was found just inside the south-west corner of the cist. A small patch of brown ÔearthyÕ silt (40133) was also identified in this south-west corner. This deposit partially underlay the ceramic vessel and would appear to represent the deposition, deliberate or accidental, of a small quantity of soil in the cist chamber before the pot was placed.

The interior of the cist was empty except for a 0.05m deep patch of very loose, mid to dark brown silty sand, with a high organic component (40177). An almost complete but broken pottery vessel, a Short Necked Beaker with large scale incised chevrons (sf4102), was found on and within this deposit in the eastern corner of the cist. So we likely had a totally degraded crouched inhumation here

Tothill St, EBA inhumations, Burial 176: crouched remains of a moderately well preserved (41.3% complete) single subadult aged 12Ð17 years at death (Fig 8). This individual lay on their right side with the head to the west, facing downslope to the south. A single calibrated radiocarbon date of 2015Ð1772 cal BC (UBA 22902, 3555±35 BP) was obtained from a tooth. The grave backfill [174] contained a small sherd identified as the lower part of the collar of a collared urn, together with some fragments of fired clay.

Tothill St, EBA inhumations, Burial 747: it contained the truncated and mixed (possibly crouched) remains of at least two subadults, whose fragmented skulls appear to have lain at opposite ends of the grave. The older of the two was moderately well preserved (24% complete) and aged 6Ð11 years at death;

Tothill St, EBA inhumations, Burial 747: Of the double (or possible triple) the younger was poorly preserved (14.9% complete) and aged 1Ð5 years. Heavy dental wear to several teeth suggested the presence of a third, older, individual in the grave, although no further adult skeletal elements could be identified.

The cist contained human bones including the majority of the cranium in the southeast corner of the cist space, several long bones and other bones including ribs and vertebral fragments.The placement of the human remains within the cist suggests the possibility of an in-situ primary burial (particularly the relative positions of the cranium, arm bones,  ribs and vertebral fragments). However, the possibility of the bones having been redeposited remains due to the placement of the disarticulated leg bone and hip found above the other bones.The extant disarticulated hip suggests a young female adult individual- aged 26-35

The cremated remains recovered after the discovery of the urn comprise mainly small bone slivers. Bones as small as this offer no help in identification of sex or stature. The only useful clue lies with the half-a-dozen teeth. Their small size, shallow roots, and lack of abrasion, point to a child's milk-teeth (Field and Calkin 1974).

(Wells in Knocker 1959, 143-4) B2: Hundreds of fragments of cremated bone. Few of these fragments were more than a few millimetres in length, many were less than one millimetre. Some were identifiable as human; none was identifiable as non-human. It was possible to define an adult of unknown age and sex and there was no evidence to suggest the presence of more than one body. The cremation had been carried out with fair efficiency. The actual site of cremation may have been on an area of ferruginous gravel covered by a thin top soil. A large amount of bone, charcoal and ash was somewhat carelessly gathered up and placed in the urn (Knocker 1959, 143-4)

(Wells in Knocker 1959, 144) B4: A small quantity of charcoal and ash in which minute fragments recognisable as bone could be detected. No fragment was more than a millimetre or two in length and none could be anatomically identified with certainty. It is highly probable that these are the cremated remains of a single infant or child but this cannot be definitely proved

(Wells in Knocker 1959, 144) B5: Cremated bone fragments. Very few of these pieces of bone were more than a few millimetres in length, but identifiable fragments include part of an axis odontoid process, part of an ulna and some cancellous tissue probably from a femoral head. The total mass was about 2,500 c.c. and represents the cremation of an adult of unknown sex and age. No evidence of more than one subject can be obtained. This pot contained very little charcoal. It suggests that the cremation was very efficiently carried out, though the survival of the odontoid process and its appearance, hints at deficient oxygenation of the pyre beneath the body due to poor stoking. The calcined bones seem to have been picked carefully out of the ashes and cleaned of charcoal and other detritus before being placed in the funerary receptable.

(Wells in Knocker 1959, 144) B9: This again strongly suggests a child's cremation but nothing survived that can prove it to be so. A few minute fragments identifiable as bone are the only surviving evidence.

(Wells in Knocker 1959, 144) B11: Small quantities of cremated bone. The remains are insufficient to provide much information, but we can say that there is no evidence suggesting the presence of more than one body. This was probably an adolescent of unknown sex. Little soot was present and it is probable that the cremation took place at a high temperature. The fragments of bone were distributed more or less evenly throughout the compact mass in the urn

Human bone from a crouched adult male inhumation burial within a cist. The higher part of the body was fairly well-preserved as it was covered by the sandy matrix of layer. However, the underside did not survive so well as it lay directly upon the slate slabs of the bottom of the cist and had been damaged by the acidity of the rock.The position of the bones within the grave appears to indicate a degree of post-mortem disturbance or collapse of the body, as the skull was lying too far away from the pelvis. This may simply be due to burial within a cist, with the potential for movement within the void before the chamber collapsed and was filled with soil. There was evidence for some dental and bony pathology in the main skeleton, which indicated that he probably suffered from some pain in his jaw, neck and lower back. He also had a fractured rib which may have been caused by a fall or a deliberate blow to his side, but it healed well and probably would not have caused too much discomfort after this. Well-developed muscle markings and the strain showing in the bones of his back indicate that his lifestyle was not sedentary, and it is likely that he was involved in some form of manual labour. He may have had a fracture of one toe at some point, and a pulled muscle in his groin. Taken together, this indicates an active life with some potential for injury (Anderson in Jones 2009-10, 87).

Portesham Farm mirror burial (Fitzpatrick 1997): Flexed inhumation burial of a woman, aged 26-45 years, with her head to the north-east and lying on her left hand side with her hands extended down towards her knees. Disturbed by metal-detecting.Badly fragmented bone, mostly due to post-burial soil compression. Much of it was also stained a dark brown, probably from some adjacent organic material. c. 80% skeletal fragments present. Signs of degenerative bone disease, arthritis, tooth loss and wear, tooth decay and a dental abscess.

<Johns 2002-3, Bryher>: Very poorly preserved crouched inhumation skeleton , laid on its right side with its head to the north and facing to the west.<Mays et al in Johns 2002-3>: Survival of bone was very poor. Less than 150g of bone fragments were present (precise weighing of remains was impossible due to firmly adherent soil being present on many fragments) and these were mainly long-bone and skull fragments. The surfaces of the long-bone fragments were heavily eroded; theskull fragments a little less so. The only long-bone fragment that was identifiable to skeletal element came from the distal part of a femur shaft. Tooth crown fragments were preserved, although only the enamel component survived; there was no dentine.

<Grave 7003/MDO37212>: The crouched burial of an adult male, badly disturbed by ploughing.The partial and disarticulated remains of a skeleton disturbed by ploughing, and with no visible grave cut. No skull was recovered, but the skeleton was that of an adult male between 26 and 35 years old, and around six feet tall. Examination of the bones revealed evidence of osteoarthritis in the right hand and spine, and spinal disc disease.

<Grave 7624/MDO37213>: The crouched burial of an adult female in poor health.The skeleton was an adult female between 36-45 years old, lying flexed on her right side and facing east with legs bent at right angles to the spine and arms tucked against the chest with the left hand over the jaw and the right hand next to the face. Examination of the bones revealed evidence of a possible poor diet and anaemia, osteoarthritis, dental caries and plaque.

<Grave 7053/MDO37218>: The crouched burial of a young female.The skeleton was that of a young female between 18 and 25 years old. Examination of the bones, revealed no evidence of pathology, unusual for this site. The skeleton was in a crouched position on her right side, facing west, with one hand under the pelvis.

<Grave 7104/MDO37222>: The crouched burial of an adolescent of uncertain sex.The body lay crouched on the left side, facing east and with the hands under the knees.The skeleton was an adolescent around 12-14 years of age of uncertain sex. Examination of the bones revealed evidence of septic arthritis in the left hip and possibly poor nutrition.

<Grave 7264/MDO37226>: The crouched burial of a young man, inserted into an earlier grave.The skeleton was that of a young male of between 18 and 25 years of age. The upper body was extended with the right hand by the pelvis, and the legs were tightly flexed. The upper body appeared to have slumped into a void left by the underlying decaying burial. Examination of the bones revealed evidence of vertebral disc problems, possible benign neoplastic disease and non-specific skull lesions.

<Grave 7565/MDO37231>: The burial of a man in a crouched postion with grave goods in the form of two bowls in Poole Harbour ware and animal bones representing a food offering.It consisted of the almost complete skeleton of an adult male, in a crouched position with head to the south east. Examination of the bones revealed evidence of possible dietary deficiency, a healed hand fracture, and several pathologies including osteoarthritis, degenerative changes in the spine, and tooth plaque.
<Murden 2014, Langton Herring>: Female aged 18-23 years old.

Drew & Piggtt 1936: 80. <the burial consisted of the remains oftwo individuals : the elder, probably a female of about 20, being represented only by two femoral fragments which were found together above the more complete remains of the skeleton of a child, about a year and a half old, which lay in a shallow grave, with a maximum depth of only 0.7 feet below the surface. The child's skull, in a fair state of  reservation, lay to the SE, but the lower jaw lay a foot away to the sw, while on top of the legs, which appeared to have been drawn up, lay a complete beaker of type ' B,' on its side, with its mouth towards the head of the skeleton. The presence of remains of two individuals suggests either a later insertion disturbing the earlier burial and itself subsequently almost entirely removed, or that the femoral fragments represent the sole remnant of a burial originally accompanying that of the child.

pit is 0.28 m in diameter and 0.80 m deep. An inverted enlarged Food Vessel, containing a cremation , had beer placed in the lower pit. its rim resting on a black ash soil which had also been tipped around the vessel, leaving the base of the pot exposed. The ashy layer was then capped with chalk and rubble, whilst the upper pit seem to have silted up naturally. The cremation contained the bones of a single adult. Charcoal of oak more than fifteen years old from the lower filling gave a date of 1620 ± 40 be (BM 2326).

This contained, within a limited area, the fragmented and partly extended skeleton of an infant aged between eighteen months and two years. It is likely that this child was suffering or had suffered some nutritional disturbance. A Food Vessel had been placed over the legs , and the grave filled with large chalk rubble. A series of rounded flint nodules was in the filling at the level of the body, whilst its upper filling contained part of a saddle quern.

An inverted plain Food Vessel Urn was set on a layer of burnt silt 0.01 m above the bottom of the pit. This contained the cremated remains of an adult and an infant aged between five and seven years. The pit was then filled with a fine brown earth. The bottom of the pot had been lost to the plough.
Cremation of child c. 5-7 years old

On the bottom of the pit was a layer of burnt silt , and above this was an inverted Collared Urn containing the cremated remains of an infant between three and five years old. The pit had been infilled with alternating layers of chalk rubble and finer chalk wash, as if there had been intervals in the filling when the upper part of the feature remained open.

An inverted Collared Urn had been placed directly on the base or the pit in a layer offine silt. There was a small quantity of cremated bone also on the base of the pit, representing an adult. The main deposit of cremated remains from within the urn was of another adult. Underneath the urn were two bone awls and a bronze awl, together with a struck flint flake. There was some charcoal just above the base of the urn. The upper part of the feature seems to have filled in with natural silt, indicating that it might have been open for some time. Charcoal from young wood at the bottom or the feature gave a date or 1550 ± 130 be (BM 2 I90R).

This is quite an unusual association for Cornwall and Beakers in general. Handled Beaker with a cremation deposit (at the time of discovery in 1964 it was only the 2nd Beaker to have been found in Cornewall) - see Quinnell and Jones 2006: Skull, mandible, limb bones and extremities too represented. Fully adult and possibly female although not 1-00% certain (determined on basis of the sinus bones being quite thin) Unburnt bones from cist - Unburnt bones from cist. These were too crumbled for any determination even as between man and a lower animal. The mass seems to consist exclusively of fragments of long boneÑpossibly a tibia, but nothing can be said beyond this. If contemporary with the cremated remains, it is possible that it represented a joint of meat put in as a funerary offering, but this is only a guess from its unburnt condition.Note the cist contained a handled Beaker and nearby two unburnt bones which could not be identified (were they the same individual as the burnt remains?) . The cist was then deliberately filled with soil containing fragments of cremated human bone, haematite, small water-worn pebbles, charcoal, and sherds from a second and possibly a third Beaker, and of Trevisker Ware. <Moore and Wilson 1995, 238 Midskaill>: The Midskaill cramp ... contained a consistently higher level of phosphorus and calcium in proportions similar to those found in the mineral apatite, which constitutes bone. The cramp from Midskaill therefore appears to represent actual cremation material, albeit in vitrified form.

<Gooney 2015, Knowe of Skea Burial 6096>: SUERC-27922; Scottish Universities Environmental Research Centre; 2070+/- 30; 80 cal BC to cal AD 0 (95% probability).The legs and pelvis of the adult (6096) were partly articulated, and this individual originally lay on the right side with the legs in a crouched position (E-W, facing right).<hr_notes>: Adult: probably middle or older adult. Child: early child suggested by the lengths of long bone fragments.(6096) SF284 consisted of the remains of an adult male and a child; site notes say a wall was built over the remains in this area. As a consequence, the bones were in a fragmentary condition (no skulls, long bones broken) and fragments from adjacent burials were mixed in with this deposit. A large amount of animal bone, sheep ribs in particular, were collected with these remains.There were a number of old cuts/strikes caused by sharp implements to the long bones of (6096) which most likely occurred after burial when the remains were at least partly skeletonised (121). This is interpreted as occuring at the time the wall was built over this and other nearby burials (186).This person also had a long-term condition that had developed into osteoarthritis of the knee which would have been painful and affectedmobility.

Inverted urn containing the incomplete cremated bone of a male c50, a small quantity of oak charcoal, and a small bronze knife-dagger. The urn was biconical, ribbon handled, decorated with cord-impressed chevron pattern, early of its kind and set on soft clay lying on a slab of shillet. Some ash and charcoal was scattered by the pit edge. The urn may have been set upright before being inverted to judge from two circular impressions left in the soft clay lying on a slab of shillet at the base of the pit - the outer ring was the same size as that of the urn rim. Pit was covered with a large slate capstone.This could be a male but not 100% certain, as no sexually dimorphic traits were noted505g of bone This cremation deposit, which weighed 504.7 g, comprised a small quantity of white, calcined bone, which was highly fragmented. All fragments were greater than 5mm insize, the majority over 10mm (90.5%), and were generally well-preserved and sharp-edged with no evidence of predepositional erosion or post-excavation damage. A total of 45.9% (232 g) were identifiable fragments. No regions of the skeleton were duplicated, all regions were represented, and no fragments diagnostic of juvenile or infant remains were present, suggesting the burial represented the whole body of a single adult. There were insufficient sexually dimorphic elements preserved to provide an estimation of sex. Those criteria used for sex estimation in the original bone report (Cornwall 1965), with the exception of the supraorbital ridge of the frontal bone, are no longer considered reliable indicators. Although there were insufficient indicators preserved to provide a more accurate estimation of age, a tooth with veryworn enamel, a fragment of auricular surface characteristic of an older adult, and the presence of spinal pathologies usually associated with older adults, comprising osteoarthritic porosity of a cervical vertebra (articular facet), and osteophytosis of several vertebrae, are consistent with an adult of more advanced years. A broad estimate of >40 years was therefore attributed to this individual.

<Harlyn Bay (Jones et al 2011, 91)>:The cremation deposit may have represented as many as five individuals. The nature of some of the porous bone fragments may indicate the presence of an individual of less than 2 years of age. The ageing information from dentition and skeletal material indicates further individuals of 3Ð4 years, around 6 years, and around 14 years. A single fused cranial fragment appears to indicate an additional adult individual. The total weight of the cremated bone that could be released from the surrounding matrix was 730 g. An estimate of the remaining material would give a weight of 900Ð1100 g.The vessel contents represented a mixture of burnt bone from a minimum of five individuals, with a little animal boneThis is unusual to have so many individuals in a single vessel (possibly a record for the EBA!)

a vault formed by four large stones, placed on the hedges (sic) was discovered, containing two human skeletons. One of the skeletons appeared to have been placed  in a sitting posture: the other appeared to have been placed in a reclining position, close to the side of the vault, with the arms crossed on the breast. The bones were nearly in a perfect state: the skeleton first mentioned appear (sic) to have been that of a man of mature age; the skull being without a visible fissure: the teeth large and the thigh bones straight. Old male

The remains of his companion appear to be those of a young female; the fissure in the skull being very apparent; the teeth small, and the thigh bones curved. They were both evidently persons of short stature, neither of the thigh bones being more than 16 inches in length: the sculls were also short and the os frontis of both very prominent. At the foot of the vault was an urn of earthenwareYoung female

There was at least 60 or 70 skeletons found, some crouched. The skeletons in each grave lay N-S in several tiers, one above the other, the heads of the skeletons of one tier lying N and the next one S and so on alternatively. 5 or 6 tiers were noted in 1 grave and 6 skulls in each tier - suggesting 60 or 70 skeletons. In the E end they were crouched but in W end they were flexed on sides with heads to the E. They were then infilled with stones thrown in rather carelessely. It was evident that they had never been disturbed since the bodies had been placed in the grave and that they had all been interred at the same time.

Mountain Barrows, Pelynt, Pelynt 2 (Higgins in Jones and Quinnell 2013):PELYNT 2This deposit comprised a quantity of predominantly white, calcined/oxidised bone. Fragment size was generally large, with 83.1% of the total deposit measuring greater  than 10 mm. The remaining fragments measured 5Ð10 mm (4.5%), with 12.4% less than 5 mm. The bone fragments were generally well-preserved and sharp-edged with no evidence of pre-depositional  erosion,  but  some  evidence of post-excavation fragmentation was indicated by ÔfreshÕ fractures.The weight of cremated bone (2788 g) is within the expected range (57Ð3000 g) for an undisturbed burial of a single cremated adult from an archaeological context, but above the average (1525.7 g) for the Bronze Age (McKinley 1997; 2000). In total, 76% of the deposit (2123 g) comprised identifiable fragments. No regions of the skeleton were duplicated, and no fragments diagnostic of juvenile or infant remains were present, indicating the burial represented an adult individual. All regions of the skeleton (skull, axial, upper limb, lower limb) were well represented. A large proportion of the bones of the hands and feet were present, also suggesting the deposit represented the Ôwhole bodyÕ of an adult.Pelvic morphology, assessed from large fragments of pubic symphysis and sacrum, suggested the  individual was of male sex and, although observable, cranial sexually dimorphic traits were scored as either female or probable female, the morphology of the pelvis is considered more reliable. In addition, the general robusticity of the skeleton is consistent with a male. However the individual has been assigned as probable male. A fully accurate estimation of age at death was not possible but the fusion of the spheno- occipital suture and completed eruption of the maxillary dentition, including the 3rd molar, indicate an age of at least 20Ð25 years, and the right pubic symphysis (stage III) a probable age of 22Ð35 (mean 28.7) years. Taken together with several other contra-indicators of advanced years the estimated age at death is 22Ð35 years.Borlase (1872, 196) also notes that:' Not a particle of charcoal or ashes could be detected among the fragments of bone'. The clean state of the bone is supported by Higgins 2013).Dates on cremated bone: SUERC-38742, 3525 ± 30BP (1935Ð1756 cal BC), SUERC-38743, 3565 ± 30 BP (2021Ð1777 cal BC), and SUERC-38744, 3575 ± 30 BP (2041Ð1956 cal BC). The radiocarbon determinations provide a date for the burial and the deposition of the flint knife in the first quarter of the 2nd millennium.

St Stephen's College, N Foreland (Boast 2004): Inhumation burial [skeleton 1214] within pit [1158].Anderson in Boast 2004, Appendix 10: 'A practically complete skeleton, missing part of the right ilium and the manubrium. The majority of the bones are solid and well-preserved. However, the facial area, cranial base as well as the spine and the ribs are fragmentedand incomplete. Several small bones found in close proximity to the skeleton were found to belong to this individual.'Detailed pathological analysis identified: squatting facets; significant ante-mortum tooth loss, minor congenital vertebrae deformity; Schmorls's nodes (evidence of severe strain to the back); only minor evidence for osteoarthritis; a well-healed fractured rib; a fused mandible/skull, meaning that this woman would barely have been able to open her jaw and would have to have eaten a very specialised diet.

Cnip Cairn Area A burial (Lelong 2018, 6-9):Hr: The human remains were in a formal arrangement that appeared at first to represent a crouched burial, lying on the right side. However, on excavation the skeleton proved to be incomplete and not fully articulated. The body may have been in several parts Ð head, thorax and lower body Ð with a right arm and a lower left leg lying separate. The slight dislocation of several vertebrae also suggests an advanced state of decomposition. Osteological analysis established that the remains on the whole were adolescent in age and possibly male.SUERC-30853; Human bone: left rib; Ê3435±35 BP; 1745Ð1655 cal BC (95% confidence)All of the individuals interred in Area A were excarnated by exposure above ground, then reburied close to the cairn (Booth in Lelong 2018, 29).

Cnip Cairn Area A burial (Lelong 2018, 6-9): Hr: Closer analysis and radiocarbon dating established that parts from at least two other individuals were represented. Additional elements include a tooth and several bones from hands and feet; one hand bone duplicated a bone in the articulated left hand of the main burial. All of these elements came from older individuals than that (or those) represented by the main burial: they were larger, fully fused and less eroded.All of the individuals interred in Area A were excarnated by exposure above ground, then reburied close to the cairn (Booth in Lelong 2018, 29).

Cnip Cairn Area D burial (Lelong 2018, 14-16):Hr: The pit held the remains of an infant, aged birth ± two months, lying on its back in the foetal position with the head to the south-east, facing north.SUERC-30872; Human bone: femur shaft fragment (Sk 3); 3375±35; 1740 to 1645 cal BCSUERC-30873; Human bone: infant femur (Sk 3); 3440±35; 1750 to 1675 cal BCThe stillborn was buried immediately after death  (Booth in Lelong 2018, 29).

Cnip Cairn Area C burial (Lelong 2018, 9-14):Cluster 1:Hr: On the north side of a mixed sandy layer, people placed a cluster of 112 disarticulated bones and bone fragments, representing at least two probable adults, an infant and a sub-adult of unknown age. These remains were dominated by bones of the chest region, hands and feet, some skull fragments, teeth and parts of long bones. There were no complete long bones, but some ends and fragments of arm and leg bones from individuals of different ages.All of the individuals interred in Area C were excarnated by exposure above ground, then reburied close to the cairn (Booth in Lelong 2018, 29).

Cnip Cairn Area C burial (Lelong 2018, 9-14):Clusters 2 and 3:Hr: Two further clusters of human bones (comprising c. 100 elements in total) were deposited on a separate layer of sand, adjacent to Cluster 1. These clusters lay roughly east/west and parallel to each other, and the sand was stained darker brown around the bones. The bones represented at least two adults, probably females, an infant and a child of six or seven. The skeletal elements represented were similar to those in Cluster 1 although more pelvic and long bones were identified, including an articulated adult radius and ulna. Other skeletal elements were arranged in broadly correct anatomical order even though they were not articulated. Elements from individuals of different ages were often combined.All of the individuals interred in Area C were excarnated by exposure above ground, then reburied close to the cairn (Booth in Lelong 2018, 29).

The skeleton lay flexed, on the left side, facing northwest, with the head bent back and the hands drawn up in front of chest. The feet were not recovered. Contraction into a smaller area than the grave might suggest an organic container. There were three tubular bone beads in the head area, one made from the tibia of a large bird, perhaps a swan, and a flint flake in front of the hands. All but the skull was covered by a tabular flint cairn built directly over the body. C

Artic skel of young juvenile with prematurely fused cranial sutures. Observation was also hampered by the fact that the burial was discovered, recorded, and lifted in heavy rain on the last day of the excavation. Given the uncertain stratigraphy in this shallow NE butt, bones from a child of comparable age found in this area and attributed to L10 (phase III, HH76 2999), may possibly have been displaced from the burial, since they show no duplicates with it. The unusual cessation of the upper slot well short of the NE butt may reflect its having been truncated by the insertion of this burial. Hardy's Monument, Portesham (Thompson and Ashbee 1957) secondary burial 4: one of three urned cremation burials in upright urns with fiat pieces of stone (iron stone?) fitting over the top as lids. The burnt remains occupied the lower part of the vessels, but as the rims had crumbled some gravel had fallen in. All three urns were just below the surface, so that the rims had badly decayed whereas the bases were in much better condition.gg: This urn is 15 inches high and 13 inches in diameter at the top and is of hard, smoothed, dark-cored ware. It has a plain internally bevelled rim; a cavetto forms the upper storey of the pot. Thus there is a carination upon which two opposing solid near-cylindrical handles have been set. These trail slightly at their bases, their ends having been flattened by the potter's finger tips, the prints of which remain. The urn bears no decoration, although probablyafter drying an attempt had been made to bore a hole from each side at a point just below the rim. This is identified as an enlarged food vesselhr: cremated remains, no further info
